Notes.Title: Medium-Term Scheduling Overview
Notes.Content: Medium-term scheduling is necessary when memory is limited and processes require more memory than available. When there is insufficient main memory, the scheduler can select some processes (e.g., blocked or lower-priority) to swap out of memory to free up resources. If there is enough memory available, it can swap in processes that had been swapped out.
Notes.Wrong_Content: Medium-term scheduling is necessary when memory is limited and other processes require more. When there is insufficient main memory, the scheduler can select some processes (e.g., blocked or lower-priority) to swap out of memory space to free up resources. If there is enough memory, it can swap in processes.

Notes.Title: Types of Scheduling
Notes.Content: Types of Scheduling: Long-term, Short-term, and Medium-term scheduling are key concepts in operating systems. Long-term scheduling determines which processes are admitted to the system for processing, short-term scheduling decides which of the ready, in-memory processes are to be executed (commonly referred to as CPU scheduling), and medium-term scheduling is used to temporarily remove processes from main memory and place them in secondary storage, thus managing the degree of multiprogramming.
